DevOps Lab Answers

This document lists commands and human-readable explanations for each requested task. Screenshots are not attached here; include them when preparing the final submission document.

1. Creating and Renaming Files/Directories

Commands:
- mkdir -p test_dir
- touch test_dir/example.txt
- mv test_dir/example.txt test_dir/renamed_example.txt

Explanation:
Create a new directory named test_dir with mkdir -p (the -p makes parent dirs if needed). touch creates an empty file example.txt inside that directory. mv renames example.txt to renamed_example.txt.

2. Viewing File Contents

Commands:
- cat /etc/passwd
- head -n 5 /etc/passwd
- tail -n 5 /etc/passwd

Explanation:
cat prints the full contents of /etc/passwd to stdout. head -n 5 prints only the first five lines. tail -n 5 prints only the last five lines. Note: on some systems /etc/passwd may require read permissions but is usually world-readable.

3. Searching for Patterns

Command:
- grep --line-number "root" /etc/passwd

Explanation:
grep searches /etc/passwd for the literal string "root". The --line-number option adds the matching line numbers to the output, which is useful for reference.

4. Zipping and Unzipping

Commands:
- zip -r test_dir.zip test_dir
- unzip -d unzipped_dir test_dir.zip

Explanation:
zip -r recursively compresses the test_dir directory into test_dir.zip. unzip -d unzipped_dir extracts the archive into the new directory unzipped_dir.

5. Downloading Files

Command:
- wget https://example.com/sample.txt -O sample.txt

Explanation:
wget downloads the file at the provided URL. -O sample.txt writes the downloaded content to sample.txt. If wget is not installed, curl -LO can be used instead.

6. Changing Permissions

Commands:
- touch secure.txt
- chmod a=r secure.txt

Explanation:
Create secure.txt with touch. chmod a=r sets read-only permission for all users (owner, group, others) and clears write/execute bits.

7. Working with Environment Variables

Command:
- export MY_VAR="Hello, Linux!"
- echo $MY_VAR

Explanation:
export sets MY_VAR in the current shell and marks it for child processes. echo prints the variable's value. To persist this variable across sessions, add the export line to ~/.bashrc or ~/.profile.

